JOHN GOTTMAN: No, you take it.

00:02:14.930 --> 00:02:15.888
JULIE GOTTMAN: No, you.

00:02:15.888 --> 00:02:17.721
[LAUGHTER] OK.

00:02:17.721 --> 00:02:18.220
All right.

00:02:18.220 --> 00:02:19.400
So--

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:19.790
JOHN GOTTMAN: She
got the microphone.

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:20.530
JULIE GOTTMAN: Is this on?

00:02:20.530 --> 00:02:21.155
LOGAN URY: Yes.

00:02:25.419 --> 00:02:26.460
JULIE GOTTMAN: All right.

00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:30.180
So the four horsemen--
how many of you

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:32.301
have heard of the four
horsemen of the apocalypse?

00:02:32.301 --> 00:02:32.800
Yeah?

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:33.570
Heard of it?

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:34.230
OK.

00:02:34.230 --> 00:02:37.770
So these are the big
predictors of demise

00:02:37.770 --> 00:02:43.890
in relationships,
for really destroying

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:45.150
the path of relationships.

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:47.830
The first one is criticism.

00:02:47.830 --> 00:02:52.240
Which is, talking
down to your partner,

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:57.176
blaming your partner for a
problem in a relationship.

00:02:57.176 --> 00:03:00.600
Blaming the problem on a
personality flaw, basically.

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:03.030
Telling your partner they're
lazy, they're a slob,

00:03:03.030 --> 00:03:04.610
they're a jerk.

00:03:04.610 --> 00:03:07.820
All of those lovely words
that we hat to hear, right?

00:03:07.820 --> 00:03:09.760
The second one is contempt.

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:11.880
And contempt is even worse.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:15.560
Contempt is criticism
but from a place

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:18.380
on high, superior position.

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:24.075
So, it's sort of like
this, do you remember

00:03:24.075 --> 00:03:26.400
when you were a teenager?

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:28.720
Do you remember when your
parents said terrible things

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:29.530
to you?

00:03:29.530 --> 00:03:32.090
And you would go [SIGH].

00:03:32.090 --> 00:03:33.900
Remember that expression?

00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:36.290
That's an expression
of contempt.

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:41.500
So if you see that in your
partner, that's trouble.

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:44.690
Sarcasm, abuse.

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:47.850
Kind of abusive put-downs.

00:03:47.850 --> 00:03:49.670
You're such a bitch.

00:03:49.670 --> 00:03:55.280
That kind of stuff, not said
lightly, really is contempt

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:57.360
and what we've learned
about contempt,

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:00.456
was that it was the
worst predictor,

00:04:00.456 --> 00:04:04.310
the most powerful predictor
of relationship demise.

00:04:04.310 --> 00:04:08.830
And not only did it predict
relationships going down,

00:04:08.830 --> 00:04:12.990
the number of
contempt expressions

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:15.970
that a listener
heard in 15 minutes

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:20.200
predicted how many infectious
illnesses the listener

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:21.780
would have in the next month.

00:04:21.780 --> 00:04:22.880
Isn't that incredible?

00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:24.450
So, it's frightening.

00:04:24.450 --> 00:04:29.670
So, contempt actually erodes
the immune system as well as

00:04:29.670 --> 00:04:32.550
the heart, the relationship.

00:04:32.550 --> 00:04:35.710
The third horseman
is defensiveness.

00:04:35.710 --> 00:04:39.540
And defensiveness
is usually either,

00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:42.130
I did too pay the
bills, you know,

00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:44.350
kind of that righteous
victim thing?

00:04:44.350 --> 00:04:46.480
Or counter-attack.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:50.330
Oh yeah, well, you didn't
pick up the dry cleaning.

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:51.890
The counter-attack.

00:04:51.890 --> 00:04:55.120
Defensiveness is the
hardest one to eliminate.

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:58.620
How many of us have
been defensive?

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:00.100
Like all of us, right?

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.970
So John and I are
continually still working

00:05:02.970 --> 00:05:05.590
that, after 30 years.

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:06.780
It's tough.

00:05:06.780 --> 00:05:11.530
So defensiveness is a
response to feeling attacked,

00:05:11.530 --> 00:05:13.880
that's why we get defensive.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:17.070
The fourth one we
call stonewalling.

00:05:17.070 --> 00:05:20.970
And this was my darling's
brilliant research

00:05:20.970 --> 00:05:23.880
break-through, one
of them, one of many,

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.940
which related stonewalling,
which means completely shutting

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:30.560
down in the middle
of a conversation,

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:35.660
and not giving any response
at all, no head nods,

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:38.670
looking away,
usually, looking down,

00:05:38.670 --> 00:05:42.360
and, you know, hoping the
ogre sitting across from you

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:44.080
will go away.

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:45.290
That's stonewalling.

00:05:45.290 --> 00:05:49.260
And why John discovered,
was that typically,

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:52.590
when people were stonewalling,
their heart-rates

00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:56.810
were above 100 beats a
minute, just sitting there.

00:05:56.810 --> 00:06:00.720
Sometimes it would be as
high as 140 beats per minute,

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:02.330
really high.

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:05.810
Meaning, they were
in fight or flight,

00:06:05.810 --> 00:06:07.720
that [INAUDIBLE]
physiological arousal,

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:10.430
and that was leading
them to stonewall.

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:14.850
That's our fourth, and
it's a problem [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:15.940
There you go.

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:19.312
Now you can go out and
destroy your relationships.

00:06:19.312 --> 00:06:20.815
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:20.815 --> 00:06:22.440
LOGAN URY: That's a
great introduction.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:23.856
So, John, I read
a story about you

00:06:23.856 --> 00:06:26.070
that I really
liked, when you met

00:06:26.070 --> 00:06:28.990
the young, unimpressed publisher
of "The Seven Principles

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:31.100
for Making Marriage
Work," and he said,

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:33.290
tell me one thing in
the next 30 seconds

00:06:33.290 --> 00:06:36.040
that I can do to improve
my marriage right now.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:37.890
Can you please share
that story, as well as

00:06:37.890 --> 00:06:39.710
your favorite advice
for couples who want

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:41.360
to improve their relationships.

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:43.890
JOHN GOTTMAN: Yeah,
it was a great moment,

00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:47.960
because I was trying to convince
Random House to invest money

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:51.340
in marketing the
book, and he was

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:54.442
unimpressed with the
videotapes I presented.

00:06:54.442 --> 00:06:55.900
So he said, tell
me one thing I can

00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:59.270
do to improve my marriage
in the next 30 seconds.

00:06:59.270 --> 00:07:01.920
I said, well there's a
lot of things of the book,

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:05.230
but if I had to pick
one, I would say

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:09.390
it's honor your wife's dreams.

00:07:09.390 --> 00:07:11.775
And this guy sat
up, put on his coat,

00:07:11.775 --> 00:07:15.050
and walked out of the
meeting. [LAUGHTER] I thought,

00:07:15.050 --> 00:07:16.390
I blew that one.

00:07:16.390 --> 00:07:17.720
He's the head of marketing.

00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:22.770
So, I found out later that
he actually went home, took

00:07:22.770 --> 00:07:27.130
the subway to Brooklyn,
and he walked in

00:07:27.130 --> 00:07:28.760
and his wife was there.

00:07:28.760 --> 00:07:31.670
She said, did you get fired?

00:07:31.670 --> 00:07:32.540
He said, no, no.

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:36.572
I came home to find out
what your dreams are.

00:07:36.572 --> 00:07:39.121
Because he didn't have a clue.

00:07:39.121 --> 00:07:41.370
So they had a great conversation
that afternoon and he

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:44.777
decided to put money in
marketing the book after that.

00:07:44.777 --> 00:07:45.276
[LAUGHTER].

00:07:45.276 --> 00:07:45.670
LOGAN URY: That's so beautiful.

00:07:45.670 --> 00:07:47.880
And what's your advice for
people in the audience for what

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:48.580
they can do?

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:52.237
Maybe not in thirty seconds,
to improve their relationship?

00:07:52.237 --> 00:07:53.820
JOHN GOTTMAN: You
know, I really think

00:07:53.820 --> 00:07:55.270
Julie hit the nail on the head.

00:07:55.270 --> 00:07:59.960
Because when I thought
about it, the work that's

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:04.680
required in relationships, and
we can prove mathematically

00:08:04.680 --> 00:08:09.270
that relationships are
systems that require energy,

00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:12.349
they're dissipative
energy systems.

00:08:12.349 --> 00:08:14.015
And if anybody's
interested in the math,

00:08:14.015 --> 00:08:17.070
you could look it up in
the book that I recently

00:08:17.070 --> 00:08:18.480
published on it.

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:21.230
But based on the math model,
now, you have to do work,

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:24.310
or the relationship
deteriorates over time.

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:27.760
And I think the work
really is down-regulating

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:30.590
your own defensiveness.

00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:33.710
Which means that when your
partner is angry with you,

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:37.270
or disappointed in you, you've
hurt your partner's feelings.

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:40.639
Instead of reacting really
quickly, and saying, bullshit,

00:08:40.639 --> 00:08:41.820
I didn't do that.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:44.110
Or, it's your problem.

00:08:44.110 --> 00:08:49.280
You really way to beat, and
then when you speak you say,

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:52.380
OK I'm listening, talk to me.

00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:53.840
And I think that's the work.

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:55.790
It's really hard work.

00:08:55.790 --> 00:08:57.510
And we still work at it.

00:08:57.510 --> 00:09:01.290
So it doesn't ever
get, really, easier.

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:05.080
No one ever feels joyful about
their partner's disappointment

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:08.690
or anger with them or having you
hurt your partner's feelings.

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:10.950
It's just something that
happens all the time.

00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:14.900
But, people come to our
couples' weekend workshop,

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:17.550
and they're always
thinking, this is great,

00:09:17.550 --> 00:09:21.586
you know, I'm glad I'm here,
because she really needs this.

00:09:21.586 --> 00:09:25.550
[LAUGHTER] You know, I'm
fine, but she really needs

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:28.890
a lot of communication work.

00:09:28.890 --> 00:09:33.090
But they're always surprised and
horrified that the work really

00:09:33.090 --> 00:09:36.367
is work you have
to do on yourself.

00:09:36.367 --> 00:09:38.450
LOGAN URY: So, you talked
being a better listener,

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:40.340
but I also read your
criticism around

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:42.510
how some people think
active listening is

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:44.310
the cure all for marriages.

00:09:44.310 --> 00:09:47.220
What are some other
misconceptions around what

00:09:47.220 --> 00:09:49.290
can help save a marriage?

00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:52.150
JOHN GOTTMAN: Part of the
reason that active listening is

00:09:52.150 --> 00:09:56.790
a mistake, the idea that
every time Julie says

00:09:56.790 --> 00:09:59.920
something, if I'm listening
I paraphrase what she says

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:05.320
and summarize it, is that nobody
can listen to a person who's

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:06.800
attacking them.

00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:08.850
You know, there has
to be responsibility

00:10:08.850 --> 00:10:12.060
not just on the listener,
but on the speaker as well.

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:15.900
So we talk a lot about
softened start-up, about how

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:18.220
the masters of the
relationship really

00:10:18.220 --> 00:10:20.580
think before they
present an issue,

00:10:20.580 --> 00:10:24.090
and they try to really calm
their partner down and say,

00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:25.590
hey, this isn't
a big deal, baby,

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:28.750
but, here's what I really need.

00:10:28.750 --> 00:10:30.400
Rather than the
horseman, they're

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:33.090
pointing their
fingers at themselves,

00:10:33.090 --> 00:10:35.780
and saying this is what
I'm feeling and here's

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:39.600
a recipe for be successful
with me, instead of pointing

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:43.480
the finger at their partner and
saying, you are so, you know,

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:45.880
and all that.

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:48.500
JULIE GOTTMAN: Yeah,
let me add to that.

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:51.570
One of the big
misconceptions about how

00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:56.090
to be in a good relationship is,
first of all don't get angry,

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:58.120
anger is a bad thing.

00:10:58.120 --> 00:11:02.890
And the reality is that anger
is not a bad thing, it just is.

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:06.660
It's organic, it's part
of our brains hard wiring.

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:11.090
It's and organic think
that needs to be expressed,

00:11:11.090 --> 00:11:14.380
but how it's
expressed is they key.

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:17.460
So, as were talking
earlier, it can

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:22.060
be expressed through criticism
and through contempt, or more

00:11:22.060 --> 00:11:26.190
a description of, I'm
frustrated, I'm furious,

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:30.680
then about what, not about who.

00:11:30.680 --> 00:11:34.580
So, I'm upset that the
kitchen is still a mess.

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:38.070
The kitchen a is still
a mess is the situation

00:11:38.070 --> 00:11:42.240
you're angry about, it's not a
personality flaw of a partner.

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:45.110
And then, saying what you mean.

00:11:45.110 --> 00:11:48.300
It's so important to
say what you mean.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:50.940
And what you do need,
rather than what you don't.

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:53.123
I need you stop being a jerk.

00:11:53.123 --> 00:11:55.490
Is your partner going
to want to hear that?

00:11:55.490 --> 00:11:57.010
I don't think so.

00:11:57.010 --> 00:12:00.740
So, you know, I need you to
be kind to me when I'm being

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:05.150
interviewed in front of a
million people. [LAUGHTER] So,

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:07.188
there's-- hear that?

00:12:07.188 --> 00:12:11.835
[LAUGHTER] So
expressing your needs

00:12:11.835 --> 00:12:14.707
is also a really
important thing to do.

