00:27:22.600 --> 00:27:28.950
which we've seen in our work,
is people avoid conflict,

00:27:28.950 --> 00:27:30.190
isn't that interesting?

00:27:30.190 --> 00:27:32.820
So, John was saying something
wonderful a moment ago,

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:36.920
which is, negative
moments are magic.

00:27:36.920 --> 00:27:41.980
They are opening a door
to greater intimacy,

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:44.100
because if you process,
if you actually

00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:45.690
talk about those
negative emotions

00:27:45.690 --> 00:27:48.380
you may be having, even
about your partner, or about

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:51.110
something else, your
partner is learning what's

00:27:51.110 --> 00:27:52.690
important to you.

00:27:52.690 --> 00:27:57.230
Your partner is learning
what you really need,

00:27:57.230 --> 00:27:58.350
what you really feel.

00:27:58.350 --> 00:28:02.234
They may be learning more
about baggage from your past

00:28:02.234 --> 00:28:04.570
that you brought into
this relationship.

00:28:04.570 --> 00:28:06.380
It's all important.

00:28:06.380 --> 00:28:14.240
So, you don't avoid conflict
if you want to build trust.

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:18.840
If you do, what starts happening
is the resentment builds up,

00:28:18.840 --> 00:28:19.786
right?

00:28:19.786 --> 00:28:20.910
You're unhappy about stuff.

00:28:23.860 --> 00:28:26.360
You are not talking about
it, you get more, and more,

00:28:26.360 --> 00:28:27.980
and more unhappy.

00:28:27.980 --> 00:28:30.030
And the more the
resentment builds,

00:28:30.030 --> 00:28:33.700
the more distance
grows between you,

00:28:33.700 --> 00:28:36.790
and then eventually you
grow quite lonely, right?

00:28:36.790 --> 00:28:39.990
Because you've been looking
to your partner for a deeper

00:28:39.990 --> 00:28:42.580
connection, and it ain't there.

00:28:42.580 --> 00:28:44.490
So, what happens?

00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:49.660
You start comparing your partner
to somebody else, somebody

00:28:49.660 --> 00:28:54.550
at work who you just had
this lovely conversation

00:28:54.550 --> 00:28:58.085
with at the popcorn bin.

00:28:58.085 --> 00:28:59.293
You guys have popcorn, right?

00:29:04.350 --> 00:29:06.340
And that's a lovely
conversation.

00:29:06.340 --> 00:29:09.360
And you think, God that person
was so warm and so friendly

00:29:09.360 --> 00:29:14.730
and so outgoing, and you start
comparing the partner at home

00:29:14.730 --> 00:29:16.150
to this one.

00:29:16.150 --> 00:29:18.360
And it's those
negative comparisons,

00:29:18.360 --> 00:29:20.815
my partner wouldn't
do that, my partner

00:29:20.815 --> 00:29:22.900
wouldn't smile at me like that.

00:29:22.900 --> 00:29:26.401
The negative comparisons
then lead you

00:29:26.401 --> 00:29:30.970
towards confiding
in that person,

00:29:30.970 --> 00:29:32.840
and then eventually
talking to that person

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:35.490
about your
relationship, et cetera.

00:29:35.490 --> 00:29:38.120
And they're going aw,
poor dear, poor dear,

00:29:38.120 --> 00:29:39.540
and being sympathetic.

00:29:39.540 --> 00:29:43.080
And before you know
it, there's bonding

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:45.690
and eventual infidelity.

00:29:45.690 --> 00:29:48.890
So, that's one common path.

00:29:48.890 --> 00:29:51.040
How do you recover?

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:54.735
Well, first of all,
you don't lie about it

00:29:54.735 --> 00:29:56.300
in the first place.

00:29:56.300 --> 00:29:57.990
It's got to be open.

00:29:57.990 --> 00:30:02.100
If a person is deceiving and
lying about having an affair,

00:30:02.100 --> 00:30:04.480
it's a double betrayal.

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:07.710
One, going outside of monogamy,
if that's your agreement,

00:30:07.710 --> 00:30:10.400
and two, lying about it.

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:14.630
So, what needs to
happen in terms

00:30:14.630 --> 00:30:17.400
of the recovery-- and we're
going to be doing a research

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:20.780
project on this,
and typically this

00:30:20.780 --> 00:30:24.620
needs to happen in therapy, it's
very hard to do without some.

00:30:24.620 --> 00:30:27.940
First, the person
whose been betrayed

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:32.100
needs to be able to
ask all the questions

00:30:32.100 --> 00:30:35.390
they have about the
affair, and the betrayer

00:30:35.390 --> 00:30:38.830
needs to be able to
answer those questions.

00:30:38.830 --> 00:30:41.950
But, what's also
important is that person

00:30:41.950 --> 00:30:44.600
whose being betrayed
typically suffers

00:30:44.600 --> 00:30:46.900
from post-traumatic
stress disorder.

00:30:46.900 --> 00:30:48.990
You guys have all heard
about that, right?

00:30:48.990 --> 00:30:52.690
In relation to combat vets
or maybe abuse histories.

00:30:52.690 --> 00:30:55.270
Same thing happens
with an affair,

00:30:55.270 --> 00:30:57.880
that's what you're
causing your partner.

00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:00.820
So they become hyper-vigilant.

00:31:00.820 --> 00:31:06.630
They are constantly suspecting
an [INAUDIBLE], another affair.

00:31:06.630 --> 00:31:10.000
They are waking up at
night with nightmares.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:13.900
They're having intrusive
images in their mind,

00:31:13.900 --> 00:31:17.970
of you with the person, which
they don't want to have,

00:31:17.970 --> 00:31:20.080
but they're having
anyway, and their emotions

00:31:20.080 --> 00:31:23.350
are spiking all over the place,
they're having big explosions.

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:25.360
That's all PTSD.

00:31:25.360 --> 00:31:27.570
So that needs to be explained.

00:31:27.570 --> 00:31:34.180
And then, the person who's
done the betraying really

00:31:34.180 --> 00:31:40.282
needs to be able to here the
feelings of the person who

00:31:40.282 --> 00:31:42.220
has been betrayed.

00:31:42.220 --> 00:31:46.320
So, the betrayer needs to hear
the feelings of the betrayed.

00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:47.790
Really hear them.

00:31:47.790 --> 00:31:50.560
But, here's where
therapy comes in.

00:31:50.560 --> 00:31:56.700
Therapy needs to
somewhat coach the person

00:31:56.700 --> 00:32:01.220
who's been betrayed, to not
use contempt and criticism

00:32:01.220 --> 00:32:05.580
to express the anger and pain.

00:32:05.580 --> 00:32:10.310
As that process slowly
winds down, which it does,

00:32:10.310 --> 00:32:15.100
then you look at rebuilding
marriage number two.

00:32:15.100 --> 00:32:18.620
Because an affair
destroys marriage.

00:32:18.620 --> 00:32:21.700
But you can still build
marriage number two,

00:32:21.700 --> 00:32:25.880
by opening up how to do conflict
in a much better way, how

00:32:25.880 --> 00:32:27.980
to turn toward the
other person, how

00:32:27.980 --> 00:32:30.270
to express honest admiration.

00:32:30.270 --> 00:32:34.290
And over time the
relationship is rebuilt,

00:32:34.290 --> 00:32:37.040
and oftentimes it's
stronger than ever.

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:40.340
So people definitely
do recover from affairs

00:32:40.340 --> 00:32:42.490
if they get some help

00:32:42.490 --> 00:32:43.620
LOGAN URY: Thank you.

00:32:43.620 --> 00:32:45.330
So, I want to shift
gears a little bit.

00:32:45.330 --> 00:32:47.030
You two are the
experts on marriage,

00:32:47.030 --> 00:32:49.990
and this has been a bit
year for gay marriage.

00:32:49.990 --> 00:32:52.370
And in all the
research that I study

00:32:52.370 --> 00:32:54.770
on the relationships and
marriage, so much of it

00:32:54.770 --> 00:32:56.770
is focused on
heterosexual couples.

00:32:56.770 --> 00:32:59.130
I know you've done some work
in the lesbian community.

00:32:59.130 --> 00:33:01.130
Can you talk a bit
about any differences

00:33:01.130 --> 00:33:05.210
that you see with gender
roles or any other changes

00:33:05.210 --> 00:33:07.700
in a gay relationship?

00:33:07.700 --> 00:33:10.330
JOHN GOTTMAN: My colleague
Bob Levenson and I

00:33:10.330 --> 00:33:13.390
studied committed gay
and lesbian couples

00:33:13.390 --> 00:33:18.370
for a dozen years, and we
found the same principles apply

00:33:18.370 --> 00:33:20.850
to gay and lesbian
committed relationships

00:33:20.850 --> 00:33:25.270
as to heterosexual
married couples.

00:33:25.270 --> 00:33:27.730
There were some
differences qualitatively.

00:33:27.730 --> 00:33:32.160
One really
interesting difference

00:33:32.160 --> 00:33:37.740
was that most heterosexual
couples in the subcultures

00:33:37.740 --> 00:33:40.460
in the United States,
except for Latino

00:33:40.460 --> 00:33:43.240
and Hispanic subcultures,
are very embarrassed

00:33:43.240 --> 00:33:46.190
talking about sex, even when
there's no camera there,

00:33:46.190 --> 00:33:47.750
with one another.

00:33:47.750 --> 00:33:52.790
And are very indirect
in what they asked for.

00:33:52.790 --> 00:33:56.470
They don't have a way of
initiating sex, a formal way

00:33:56.470 --> 00:33:58.110
of talking about it.

00:33:58.110 --> 00:34:01.097
And so gay and
lesbian couples are

00:34:01.097 --> 00:34:03.180
very different than
heterosexual couples that way.

00:34:03.180 --> 00:34:07.280
They're little very open
and very direct in talking

00:34:07.280 --> 00:34:09.409
about what they need sexually.

00:34:09.409 --> 00:34:11.110
But the overriding
the difference

00:34:11.110 --> 00:34:15.110
was that gay and lesbian couples
were a lot nicer to each other

00:34:15.110 --> 00:34:17.600
than heterosexual couples.

00:34:17.600 --> 00:34:22.250
They were gentler in the way
they presented their conflicts,

00:34:22.250 --> 00:34:24.380
and they were less
defensive, and there

00:34:24.380 --> 00:34:27.900
was more of a sense of humor.

00:34:27.900 --> 00:34:31.530
And we know that there's
a lot more sensitivity

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:36.820
in gay and lesbian couples
to power differentials

00:34:36.820 --> 00:34:39.389
in the relationship
and a desire--

00:34:39.389 --> 00:34:42.130
maybe because there is
less choice, only 10%

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:46.210
of the population
is gay or lesbian.

00:34:46.210 --> 00:34:48.120
Because there's less
choice, I think,

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:52.949
they're more willing to
have an equal relationship,

00:34:52.949 --> 00:34:55.750
even if there are differences
in income or education,

00:34:55.750 --> 00:34:59.634
to really make sure that there's
not that power differential.

00:34:59.634 --> 00:35:01.050
LOGAN URY: Do you
predict anything

00:35:01.050 --> 00:35:03.008
will change as it goes
from committed long-term

00:35:03.008 --> 00:35:05.870
relationships to
official marriage?

00:35:05.870 --> 00:35:09.270
JOHN GOTTMAN: Yes, I really do.

00:35:09.270 --> 00:35:13.270
I think the difference
is that they will feel,

00:35:13.270 --> 00:35:17.182
gay and lesbian couples will
feel more a part of society,

00:35:17.182 --> 00:35:21.625
rather than defensive
about who they are.

00:35:21.625 --> 00:35:25.340
They'll really be
accepted, they'll

00:35:25.340 --> 00:35:30.730
be really are treated as equals.

00:35:30.730 --> 00:35:34.050
JULIE GOTTMAN: Yeah, let me
add to that a little bit.

00:35:34.050 --> 00:35:36.840
Less positive note.

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:43.010
But first, I did the
first study in the country

00:35:43.010 --> 00:35:48.640
on when daughters were
raised by lesbian mothers,

00:35:48.640 --> 00:35:51.574
how did they turn out compared
to the daughters of hetero

00:35:51.574 --> 00:35:53.090
moms.

00:35:53.090 --> 00:35:55.840
And this was back in 1980.

00:35:55.840 --> 00:36:00.790
When kids were in
custody situations

00:36:00.790 --> 00:36:04.237
with the hetero parent,
when the mom wanted to go

00:36:04.237 --> 00:36:06.750
live a lesbian lifestyle.

00:36:06.750 --> 00:36:08.500
And the kids were
being taken away

00:36:08.500 --> 00:36:14.690
from the mother, every single
time, because she was lesbian.

00:36:14.690 --> 00:36:18.771
And they would often be given
to a heroin-addicted father,

00:36:18.771 --> 00:36:20.420
an alcoholic grandfather.

00:36:20.420 --> 00:36:24.160
They'd be given to anybody else,
but taken away from the mother.

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:27.530
So the study that I
was fortunate to do,

00:36:27.530 --> 00:36:32.560
and very supported
by many lesbian

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:36.670
moms and their daughters,
showed that, of course,

00:36:36.670 --> 00:36:38.640
the daughters, who
are now adults,

00:36:38.640 --> 00:36:42.710
were actually doing better,
having been raised by lesbian

00:36:42.710 --> 00:36:45.310
moms, in terms of
social adjustment,

00:36:45.310 --> 00:36:48.590
and there were no differences
in gender-identity and sexual

00:36:48.590 --> 00:36:49.090
orientation.

00:36:49.090 --> 00:36:50.700
It was exactly the same.

00:36:50.700 --> 00:36:55.610
So now, the thing that
I'm beginning to hear,

00:36:55.610 --> 00:36:57.552
which really me
frightens me, which

00:36:57.552 --> 00:36:59.010
you guys might want
to be aware of,

00:36:59.010 --> 00:37:05.590
is that as gay marriage
has now become the law,

00:37:05.590 --> 00:37:09.482
there are groups in America
who are trying to roll back

00:37:09.482 --> 00:37:12.242
the laws about gay adoption.

00:37:12.242 --> 00:37:17.370
Because the research
that I and many others

00:37:17.370 --> 00:37:22.620
did at that time, allowed
gay parents, lesbian parents,

00:37:22.620 --> 00:37:25.620
or gay and lesbian
couples to adopt kids.

00:37:25.620 --> 00:37:29.230
Well, now they're
trying to roll it back.

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:34.990
So, there's still tension
this issue despite the fact

00:37:34.990 --> 00:37:37.685
that, hooray, gay and
lesbians can now marry.

00:37:37.685 --> 00:37:40.260
LOGAN URY: That's
really interesting.

00:37:40.260 --> 00:37:42.050
JULIE GOTTMAN: And
subsequent research

00:37:42.050 --> 00:37:46.950
to Julie's landmark study,
has replicated that effect

00:37:46.950 --> 00:37:49.920
and show that gay
and lesbian couples

00:37:49.920 --> 00:37:52.850
are every bit as good parents.

00:37:52.850 --> 00:37:55.690
And in fact, my
personal experience,

00:37:55.690 --> 00:37:59.350
sort of trailing along as a
spouse when Julie give talks

00:37:59.350 --> 00:38:02.820
for concerned gay
and lesbian parents,

00:38:02.820 --> 00:38:05.490
was that they were
much more concerned

00:38:05.490 --> 00:38:08.990
than heterosexual parents that
will then be terrible parents,

00:38:08.990 --> 00:38:13.090
and they really go for
parental education classes

00:38:13.090 --> 00:38:14.270
and workshops.

00:38:14.270 --> 00:38:15.910
So, I think just
the opposite is true

00:38:15.910 --> 00:38:18.970
and I think it's worthwhile
raising this alarm.

00:38:18.970 --> 00:38:20.420
LOGAN URY: The
kids are all right.

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:21.210
JOHN GOTTMAN: Yes, they are.

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:22.340
JULIE GOTTMAN: Kids are great.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:24.120
LOGAN URY: So, I've been
wondering this for a long time.

00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:26.980
You're famous for your ability
to predict a couple's success

00:38:26.980 --> 00:38:29.700
rate for staying together in
a next three to five years

00:38:29.700 --> 00:38:31.810
with more than 90% accuracy.

00:38:31.810 --> 00:38:33.440
So, as you're doing
research, and you

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:36.720
see a couple that's really,
the four horseman are present,

00:38:36.720 --> 00:38:38.240
there's all these issues.

00:38:38.240 --> 00:38:40.250
Do you say anything to them?

00:38:40.250 --> 00:38:43.250
Do you say better watch
out or don't get married?

00:38:43.250 --> 00:38:45.400
JULIE GOTTMAN: (SINGING)
You better not cry.

00:38:45.400 --> 00:38:46.440
It's the season.

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:47.939
LOGAN URY: And then
I was wondering,

00:38:47.939 --> 00:38:49.980
are you ever at a coffee
shop or on an airplane

00:38:49.980 --> 00:38:51.980
and you hear a couple,
do you ever go up to them

00:38:51.980 --> 00:38:55.276
and say, listen-- [LAUGHTER]

00:38:55.276 --> 00:38:56.984
JULIE GOTTMAN: Wait,
I get to talk first.

00:38:56.984 --> 00:39:02.980
[LAUGHTER] See that's how--
he accepts influence, that's

00:39:02.980 --> 00:39:05.886
another really important
thing, in terms

00:39:05.886 --> 00:39:08.210
of successful relationships.

00:39:08.210 --> 00:39:11.100
JOHN GOTTMAN: That's
enlightened self-interest.

00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:15.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:18.910
JULIE GOTTMAN: First of
all, no we don't do that.

00:39:18.910 --> 00:39:22.554
Otherwise, we'd never get
invited to dinner. [LAUGHTER].

00:39:22.554 --> 00:39:27.400
[INAUDIBLE] out in the public--
our invitations drop down

00:39:27.400 --> 00:39:27.990
[INAUDIBLE].

00:39:27.990 --> 00:39:32.500
So, you don't typically
do that, because these

00:39:32.500 --> 00:39:34.510
are group statistics.

00:39:34.510 --> 00:39:36.630
They're all group
statistics, so there's always

00:39:36.630 --> 00:39:38.790
exceptions in group statistics.

00:39:38.790 --> 00:39:41.460
On the other hand,
I have to tell you

00:39:41.460 --> 00:39:45.940
a story, which is we have
one child, one daughter,

00:39:45.940 --> 00:39:48.580
we were really old when
we had her, so any of you

00:39:48.580 --> 00:39:51.835
who have old parents, know
that your parents will dote all

00:39:51.835 --> 00:39:55.660
over you, and hover
and protect you,

00:39:55.660 --> 00:39:59.720
So when our daughter was
two, John put her in front

00:39:59.720 --> 00:40:04.300
of the t.v. with videos
from the lab, and said

00:40:04.300 --> 00:40:08.230
what you think about how
that father, what do you

00:40:08.230 --> 00:40:09.695
think about those two?

00:40:09.695 --> 00:40:12.050
Are they doing okay or not?

00:40:12.050 --> 00:40:17.410
And we've been doing that with
her, poor thing, [LAUGHTER]

00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:20.360
we not only set up the college
fund but a psychotherapy fund.

00:40:20.360 --> 00:40:25.410
[LAUGHTER] She's the daughter
of two psychologists, so.

00:40:25.410 --> 00:40:29.080
Yeah, we rarely tell people
they should split up,

00:40:29.080 --> 00:40:31.900
but every now and
then we do, when

00:40:31.900 --> 00:40:37.840
there's definite abuse and
no clear path for change.

00:40:40.576 --> 00:40:42.450
JOHN GOTTMAN: Sometimes,
it's really painful,

00:40:42.450 --> 00:40:49.375
like we did this study of
couples having first baby,

00:40:49.375 --> 00:40:52.100
and we followed them
from a couple of months

00:40:52.100 --> 00:40:55.770
after the wedding, and
we found that 2/3 of them

00:40:55.770 --> 00:40:58.460
had a big drop in
relationship happiness

00:40:58.460 --> 00:41:01.020
in the first three years
of the baby's life.

00:41:01.020 --> 00:41:03.280
You know, 2/3 of them.

00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:07.150
And when Julie and I
designed this workshop,

00:41:07.150 --> 00:41:10.090
two day workshop called
"Bringing Baby Home,"

00:41:10.090 --> 00:41:13.740
we could reverse that
trend for almost 80%

00:41:13.740 --> 00:41:16.410
of the couples in just two days.

00:41:16.410 --> 00:41:17.620
We could do that.

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:19.735
And we were at a
restaurant recently,

00:41:19.735 --> 00:41:25.300
and I saw this young couple
and they had a new baby,

00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:28.560
and they all also had
about a five-year-old girl,

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:30.710
and they weren't
speaking to each other

00:41:30.710 --> 00:41:33.750
throughout the whole
dinner, and the glances

00:41:33.750 --> 00:41:36.040
were pretty negative.

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:37.920
And I was just dying
to go over to them

00:41:37.920 --> 00:41:40.110
and say, would you
take our workshop,

00:41:40.110 --> 00:41:43.260
[LAUGHTER] because
you can avoid all

00:41:43.260 --> 00:41:48.940
of this pain in such a short
time, and prevent this misery.

00:41:48.940 --> 00:41:52.410
But I don't feel I can do
that, go over to somebody

00:41:52.410 --> 00:41:53.010
and say that.

00:41:53.010 --> 00:41:54.060
But I would really--

00:41:54.060 --> 00:41:56.351
LOGAN URY: It's like you have
a superpower-- [LAUGHTER]

00:41:56.351 --> 00:41:57.979
JOHN GOTTMAN: Yeah, right.

00:41:57.979 --> 00:41:59.770
LOGAN URY: So I have
so many more questions

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:01.811
I'm going to just ask one,
so that we can open it

00:42:01.811 --> 00:42:04.155
up to the audience afterward,
but in my own personal

00:42:04.155 --> 00:42:06.530
research, in talking to people
about their relationships,

00:42:06.530 --> 00:42:09.072
the question I get the
most is, how do I know

00:42:09.072 --> 00:42:10.280
if I'm with the right person?

00:42:10.280 --> 00:42:11.770
And when do I settle down?

00:42:11.770 --> 00:42:13.800
And are my standards too high?

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:17.390
And through you, I discovered
to research of Don Baucom

00:42:17.390 --> 00:42:20.391
about realistic versus
idealistic standards.

00:42:20.391 --> 00:42:22.640
I was wondering if you can
talk about this, especially

00:42:22.640 --> 00:42:25.580
for people in the audience or
on YouTube who are thinking,

00:42:25.580 --> 00:42:26.830
am I'm with the right person?

00:42:26.830 --> 00:42:28.090
Or, how do I find
the right person?

00:42:28.090 --> 00:42:29.590
JOHN GOTTMAN: You
know, every couple

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:32.670
of months when I used to
watch "Oprah Winfrey," there'd

00:42:32.670 --> 00:42:36.430
be this depressed
psychiatrist on,

00:42:36.430 --> 00:42:40.920
as an expert on relationships,
I think his advice was always,

00:42:40.920 --> 00:42:42.870
lower your
expectations, you know.

00:42:42.870 --> 00:42:47.090
And he said, don't expect
anything from people,

00:42:47.090 --> 00:42:50.620
because it's really going to
be bad if you expect something,

00:42:50.620 --> 00:42:51.900
you'll always be disappointed.

00:42:51.900 --> 00:42:53.108
This guy looked so depressed.

00:42:55.950 --> 00:42:58.180
But you hear this advice
over and over again,

00:42:58.180 --> 00:43:01.710
don't expect anything, because
high expectations are the death

00:43:01.710 --> 00:43:03.310
knell of relationship.

00:43:03.310 --> 00:43:06.910
So Don Baucom, at the
University of North Carolina,

00:43:06.910 --> 00:43:11.040
spent a decade studying this,
and he found just the opposite.

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:13.730
That when people expect
to be treated well,

00:43:13.730 --> 00:43:16.240
that's what they get
in relationships.

00:43:16.240 --> 00:43:18.740
And when people have
lowered their expectations,

00:43:18.740 --> 00:43:21.960
so that they're OK
being treated like dirt,

00:43:21.960 --> 00:43:23.470
that's what they get.

00:43:23.470 --> 00:43:27.330
So his advice was
have high expectations

00:43:27.330 --> 00:43:31.897
and expect to be treated well,
and bail out a relationship

00:43:31.897 --> 00:43:33.230
if you're getting treated badly.

00:43:36.090 --> 00:43:38.380
JULIE GOTTMAN: One of
the things that I really

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:44.050
love to tell folks is,
how does your partner make

00:43:44.050 --> 00:43:47.740
you feel about yourself?

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:53.335
So if, when you're with that
partner, you feel handsome,

00:43:53.335 --> 00:43:58.780
you feel beautiful, you feel
smart, and you feel cherished.

00:43:58.780 --> 00:44:02.780
You feel like your
partner really

00:44:02.780 --> 00:44:09.310
respects you, that's a sign that
the relationship is a good one.

00:44:09.310 --> 00:44:13.354
If, on the other hand, you feel
insecure, you feel nervous,

00:44:13.354 --> 00:44:14.020
you feel scared.

00:44:14.020 --> 00:44:18.407
You feel like, God was that
a stupid thing I just said?

00:44:21.090 --> 00:44:24.290
How come they're not responding?

00:44:24.290 --> 00:44:26.070
Why are they always
looking away?

00:44:26.070 --> 00:44:28.410
Why are they looking
at the other people

00:44:28.410 --> 00:44:29.900
instead of looking at me?

00:44:29.900 --> 00:44:33.885
Those kinds of questions
indicate to you

00:44:33.885 --> 00:44:39.060
a big question mark in terms
of whether the relationship is

00:44:39.060 --> 00:44:40.249
really working for you.

00:44:40.249 --> 00:44:41.040
JOHN GOTTMAN: Yeah.

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:43.490
Let me tell a story.

00:44:43.490 --> 00:44:47.930
I was talking to somebody
in a shop, this shopkeeper,

00:44:47.930 --> 00:44:50.989
and she said I'm now really
in a good relationship,

00:44:50.989 --> 00:44:52.530
but I used to be in
this relationship

00:44:52.530 --> 00:44:55.400
where the guy always
said to me, why

00:44:55.400 --> 00:44:57.160
do you have to laugh so much?

00:44:57.160 --> 00:44:58.910
And why do you have
to laugh so loud?

00:44:58.910 --> 00:45:01.020
Can't you think
before you laugh?

00:45:01.020 --> 00:45:04.150
[LAUGHTER] That was
his message to me.

00:45:04.150 --> 00:45:07.850
And she said, when I
was thinking about it,

00:45:07.850 --> 00:45:10.420
nobody thinks before they
laugh, they just laugh

00:45:10.420 --> 00:45:11.840
or they don't laugh, right?

00:45:11.840 --> 00:45:15.550
And I'm now with somebody who
just loves the way I laugh,

00:45:15.550 --> 00:45:20.440
and I'm with this guy
and he's just perfect.

00:45:20.440 --> 00:45:21.940
LOGAN URY: That's
a beautiful story,

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:23.595
and I'm also really
happy about what

00:45:23.595 --> 00:45:25.310
you said about keeping
high standards,

00:45:25.310 --> 00:45:27.175
because I think this
community, especially,

00:45:27.175 --> 00:45:30.020
is one where people are
going to hold off until they

00:45:30.020 --> 00:45:31.180
find the right person.

00:45:31.180 --> 00:45:32.210
And I think it's
a great reminder

00:45:32.210 --> 00:45:33.876
that you shouldn't
lower your standards,

00:45:33.876 --> 00:45:37.540
