marriages in my practice,

00:46:27.660 --> 00:46:30.315
and it feels like it's a whole
different ball of wax, doing

00:46:30.315 --> 00:46:31.190
counseling with them.

00:46:31.190 --> 00:46:33.400
And I'm wondering, have
you done any research

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:36.920
on arranged marriages versus
one where, here in the US,

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:39.839
we get to select?

00:46:39.839 --> 00:46:41.630
JOHN GOTTMAN: But we
haven't systematically

00:46:41.630 --> 00:46:44.550
studied arranged marriages, but
there is quite a big research

00:46:44.550 --> 00:46:49.030
literature on this,
and I just want

00:46:49.030 --> 00:46:51.230
to say that the same
principles apply.

00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:53.130
That respect and
affection is what

00:46:53.130 --> 00:46:55.200
makes those relationships work.

00:46:55.200 --> 00:46:58.970
Now, arranged marriages
are very different when

00:46:58.970 --> 00:47:02.260
they're in the community that
has arranged the marriages,

00:47:02.260 --> 00:47:04.520
because then there is a
lot of social support,

00:47:04.520 --> 00:47:08.620
and sociologists have found
that it's not religiosity

00:47:08.620 --> 00:47:11.220
or any of that, that
determines the greater

00:47:11.220 --> 00:47:14.050
stability of arranged
marriages, but that

00:47:14.050 --> 00:47:16.020
continued social support.

00:47:16.020 --> 00:47:19.300
So, if a couple has an
arranged marriage in Calcutta,

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:22.310
then they moved to Seattle,
a very different kind

00:47:22.310 --> 00:47:23.400
of situation.

00:47:23.400 --> 00:47:25.840
And they're at some
peril, because they

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:30.390
don't have that community of
support that intervenes when

00:47:30.390 --> 00:47:32.635
he loses his job,
