00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:13.000
is that it's based on data.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:18.210
Like it was quoted earlier
that during the stonewalling,

00:51:18.210 --> 00:51:23.330
the beat rate went
up 100, 140, and that

00:51:23.330 --> 00:51:25.950
made me really curious,
is that conducted

00:51:25.950 --> 00:51:27.210
in a laboratory setting?

00:51:27.210 --> 00:51:31.880
Are couples then put
in a Tetris situation,

00:51:31.880 --> 00:51:33.530
in a lab and then studied?

00:51:37.560 --> 00:51:39.800
JOHN GOTTMAN: We've studied
them in several ways.

00:51:39.800 --> 00:51:42.610
One is a standard
kind of situations

00:51:42.610 --> 00:51:45.370
that are designed
to elicit conflict,

00:51:45.370 --> 00:51:48.520
or having them talk
about how their day went

00:51:48.520 --> 00:51:51.150
after they've been apart
for at least eight hours.

00:51:51.150 --> 00:51:54.810
But in the love lab I built
at University of Washington,

00:51:54.810 --> 00:51:57.610
couples just hang
out for 24 hours

00:51:57.610 --> 00:51:59.670
and the videotape
is just rolling,

00:51:59.670 --> 00:52:01.200
no instructions at all.

00:52:01.200 --> 00:52:02.970
So we watch them
having dinner, we

00:52:02.970 --> 00:52:05.740
watch them reading
the newspaper,

00:52:05.740 --> 00:52:08.350
cleaning up after
dinner, stuff like that.

00:52:08.350 --> 00:52:11.250
So, there you can just
look at everyday moments,

00:52:11.250 --> 00:52:13.350
and they're wearing
Holter monitors,

00:52:13.350 --> 00:52:16.660
so we're looking at their
heart rate, electrocardiogram,

00:52:16.660 --> 00:52:19.130
and when they urinate,
we take a urine sample.

00:52:19.130 --> 00:52:20.740
That measures stress hormones.

00:52:20.740 --> 00:52:22.470
We take blood from that too.

00:52:22.470 --> 00:52:24.127
But-- [LAUGHTER]

00:52:24.127 --> 00:52:26.043
LOGAN URY: There's no
cameras in the bathroom.

