So, what we saw though,
is that the couples who

00:54:54.900 --> 00:54:59.590
were successful, had a
little bit less of it,

00:54:59.590 --> 00:55:01.890
but they still did
it from time to time.

00:55:01.890 --> 00:55:04.530
But they made repairs.

00:55:04.530 --> 00:55:06.690
They made repairs.

00:55:06.690 --> 00:55:10.140
After they were critical,
after they were contemptuous,

00:55:10.140 --> 00:55:13.320
after they were too
defensive or stonewalling,

00:55:13.320 --> 00:55:16.860
they would go back and
say, you know what?

00:55:16.860 --> 00:55:22.260
I really hated how I just put
you down half an hour ago.

00:55:22.260 --> 00:55:25.650
I want to apologize
for that, and they

00:55:25.650 --> 00:55:28.550
might have a conversation
about, what was going on

00:55:28.550 --> 00:55:32.040
with you when that happened?

00:55:32.040 --> 00:55:35.240
And what we've seen
in our clinical work,

00:55:35.240 --> 00:55:38.380
it's one of the tools that we
give in our couple's workshops,

00:55:38.380 --> 00:55:46.350
that you too will get to learn,
is that when couples can go

00:55:46.350 --> 00:55:49.860
back and process a
regrettable incident,

00:55:49.860 --> 00:55:54.020
a bad fight they've had, as if
they were sitting in the upper

00:55:54.020 --> 00:55:56.450
balcony of the theatre
looking down on the stage.

00:55:56.450 --> 00:55:59.960
And saying, what the heck
happened during Act One?

00:55:59.960 --> 00:56:04.190
And understand, from your
partners point of view,

00:56:04.190 --> 00:56:05.795
what their partner
was feeling, what

00:56:05.795 --> 00:56:10.190
their partner was receiving,
and do that in both directions.

00:56:10.190 --> 00:56:13.130
Really listening to
the other person.

00:56:13.130 --> 00:56:16.710
And then owning responsibility
for whatever they contributed

00:56:16.710 --> 00:56:19.130
to that regrettable incident.

00:56:19.130 --> 00:56:23.490
It's a beautiful way
of, again, taking

00:56:23.490 --> 00:56:25.330
something regrettable
that's happened

00:56:25.330 --> 00:56:27.320
and turning it into magic.

00:56:27.320 --> 00:56:31.060
Turning it into understanding
the other person's

00:56:31.060 --> 00:56:34.830
inner-life in a much deeper way.

00:56:34.830 --> 00:56:37.700
LOGAN URY: I think we have time
for one more quick question.

00:56:37.700 --> 00:56:41.390
AUDIENCE: Thank you so
much for coming here.

00:56:41.390 --> 00:56:43.490
For those of us who
have young children

00:56:43.490 --> 00:56:47.660
but aren't able to attend
your two day workshops,

00:56:47.660 --> 00:56:49.850
what are some of
the things that are

00:56:49.850 --> 00:56:52.930
specific to couples
with young children,

00:56:52.930 --> 00:56:55.710
both in terms of the problems
that they experience,

00:56:55.710 --> 00:56:58.975
and also in terms of
strategies that they can use?

00:57:02.410 --> 00:57:08.120
JOHN GOTTMAN: Sure, one of the
things that is very important

00:57:08.120 --> 00:57:11.850
is that, when you
become a parent,

00:57:11.850 --> 00:57:16.620
you've made a huge
philosophical leap.

00:57:16.620 --> 00:57:20.760
I'm sure you experienced this
when you became a father.

00:57:20.760 --> 00:57:26.050
That you become infinitely
vulnerable, right?

00:57:26.050 --> 00:57:29.970
I mean, no question
that you'd stop a mac

00:57:29.970 --> 00:57:32.860
truck to save your kids' life.

00:57:32.860 --> 00:57:37.000
Automatically, you know that
if something bad happened

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.800
to your kid, it'd be disastrous.

00:57:39.800 --> 00:57:42.480
And you've immediately
joined the family

00:57:42.480 --> 00:57:45.890
of man, the family
of mankind, humanity.

00:57:45.890 --> 00:57:49.480
And you become so
vulnerable, and you're

00:57:49.480 --> 00:57:54.250
able to love at a level that
is beyond what you imagined.

00:57:54.250 --> 00:57:59.420
So, it's a huge change, and
loving this creature together

00:57:59.420 --> 00:58:01.730
with your wife,
with your partner,

00:58:01.730 --> 00:58:04.520
is a very powerful bond.

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:07.070
And a part of what we
teach in this workshop

00:58:07.070 --> 00:58:10.230
is how to listen to babies.

00:58:10.230 --> 00:58:14.370
How to understand babies operate
on a completely different time

00:58:14.370 --> 00:58:18.180
scale from us, much slower.

00:58:18.180 --> 00:58:22.000
And if you can slow down
and be you with your baby,

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:27.510
and enjoy the fact that there
was no toy on the planet

00:58:27.510 --> 00:58:31.070
that is as interesting to
your baby as your face,

00:58:31.070 --> 00:58:34.770
and there's no music as
interesting as your voice

00:58:34.770 --> 00:58:35.910
to that baby.

00:58:35.910 --> 00:58:38.650
And it's a hell of a lot of
fun to be with that child,

00:58:38.650 --> 00:58:40.730
and spend time with that child.

00:58:40.730 --> 00:58:46.750
And I'll tell you one really
quick story, which is-- OK,

00:58:46.750 --> 00:58:48.095
and then you get to talk.

00:58:48.095 --> 00:58:53.580
[LAUGHTER] We were talking
to a [INAUDIBLE] reservation

00:58:53.580 --> 00:58:57.580
one time, and we're talking
about the importance

00:58:57.580 --> 00:59:01.650
of listening to children,
and they were saying well

00:59:01.650 --> 00:59:03.620
people have been
telling us, speakers

00:59:03.620 --> 00:59:05.970
have been telling us to
tell stories to children.

00:59:05.970 --> 00:59:09.230
Stories about our culture
and our people, and you're

00:59:09.230 --> 00:59:10.680
telling us to listen.

00:59:10.680 --> 00:59:12.620
And I ask people,
how many of you

00:59:12.620 --> 00:59:15.450
remember what it was
like to be a kid?

00:59:15.450 --> 00:59:16.945
And some hands went up.

00:59:16.945 --> 00:59:19.230
And I said, of those
of you who remember

00:59:19.230 --> 00:59:22.670
what it was like to be
a child, how many of you

00:59:22.670 --> 00:59:27.640
had an adult who treated you
with respect and kindness

00:59:27.640 --> 00:59:29.000
and listened to you?

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:31.240
And only a few hands
stayed up, and I

00:59:31.240 --> 00:59:34.010
said would you be willing
to share your stories?

00:59:34.010 --> 00:59:37.060
And all those people
talked and wept

00:59:37.060 --> 00:59:41.110
as they talked about the fact
that my grandmother, when

00:59:41.110 --> 00:59:44.070
I walked into her room, she
would brighten and sit down,

00:59:44.070 --> 00:59:46.525
drop what she was
doing and listen to me,

00:59:46.525 --> 00:59:51.560
and celebrated me and found me
interesting, and respected me.

00:59:51.560 --> 00:59:54.330
So I think that's really
what I would recommend

00:59:54.330 --> 00:59:59.411
as the key thing, is to learn
how to listen to your child.

00:59:59.411 --> 01:00:00.160
JULIE GOTTMAN: OK.

01:00:00.160 --> 01:00:02.030
So let me ask you
something, are you sleep

01:00:02.030 --> 01:00:05.200
deprived or is your partner?

01:00:05.200 --> 01:00:06.560
AUDIENCE: Yes, and yes.

01:00:06.560 --> 01:00:09.068
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:09.068 --> 01:00:11.490
JULIE GOTTMAN: OK then,
let me just mention

01:00:11.490 --> 01:00:17.130
to you that sleep deprivation
is a biggie for young parents,

01:00:17.130 --> 01:00:24.960
and after 30 days, typically,
of interrupted night's sleep,

01:00:24.960 --> 01:00:30.510
people will-- almost everyone
will show many, many signs

01:00:30.510 --> 01:00:33.050
of clinical depression.

01:00:33.050 --> 01:00:37.055
What that means is
that young parents tend

01:00:37.055 --> 01:00:39.930
to be more irritable with one
another, a little bit more

01:00:39.930 --> 01:00:44.040
withdrawn, more exhausted,
conflict goes up.

01:00:44.040 --> 01:00:45.940
Aren't you glad
you had children?

01:00:45.940 --> 01:00:49.880
[LAUGHTER] You know,
wonderful moments too,

01:00:49.880 --> 01:00:55.420
but the work has tripled, and
you're exhausted all the time.

01:00:55.420 --> 01:00:59.320
So, part of what
we really recommend

01:00:59.320 --> 01:01:01.760
is not only listening
to your kids,

01:01:01.760 --> 01:01:03.520
but listening to each other.

01:01:03.520 --> 01:01:06.630
So having, if you can
have what we call a little

01:01:06.630 --> 01:01:08.730
ritual of connection.

01:01:08.730 --> 01:01:12.010
Which means, a time of
connecting with your partner

01:01:12.010 --> 01:01:15.160
that you can really count
on, that's predictable.

01:01:15.160 --> 01:01:20.600
If you can have a stress
reducing conversation

01:01:20.600 --> 01:01:23.295
in the evenings, even
when you're exhausted,

01:01:23.295 --> 01:01:24.890
of how was your day, dear?

01:01:24.890 --> 01:01:26.680
Tell me about your day.

01:01:26.680 --> 01:01:28.560
And each of you can
whine and complain

01:01:28.560 --> 01:01:32.820
to each other, that is really
useful, where people are just

01:01:32.820 --> 01:01:38.640
empathizing with one
another to stay connected.

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:42.240
Because when you're
so busy, parents

01:01:42.240 --> 01:01:45.540
find they don't have much time
to just talk to each other,

01:01:45.540 --> 01:01:47.480
hang out with each other.

01:01:47.480 --> 01:01:50.295
So it's really important to
build in rituals of connection

01:01:50.295 --> 01:01:51.704
to do that.

01:01:51.704 --> 01:01:56.725
That are talking about things
other than, did you call

01:01:56.725 --> 01:01:58.210
the plumber.

01:01:58.210 --> 01:01:59.660
So, that's one.

01:01:59.660 --> 01:02:04.740
Another is, if at all
possible, have a date night.

01:02:04.740 --> 01:02:08.240
Have a date night, where
you go out once a week.

01:02:08.240 --> 01:02:12.150
Even when the kids are
little you can do that.

01:02:12.150 --> 01:02:15.500
And, that third, if
you can possibly,

01:02:15.500 --> 01:02:19.030
it depends on how old your
kids are, once in a while,

01:02:19.030 --> 01:02:20.610
have an overnight.

01:02:20.610 --> 01:02:24.860
You know, just, all you'll
do to is talk about you kids.

01:02:24.860 --> 01:02:28.330
Know that, but you
won't be interrupted

01:02:28.330 --> 01:02:29.813
while you're doing that.

01:02:29.813 --> 01:02:31.540
Which is a good thing.

01:02:31.540 --> 01:02:36.720
And, they can get
our book. [LAUGHTER]

01:02:36.720 --> 01:02:37.900
JOHN GOTTMAN: [INAUDIBLE].

01:02:37.900 --> 01:02:40.540
JULIE GOTTMAN: So, our book
has all of this, but anyway.

01:02:40.540 --> 01:02:45.600
So, staying connected with your
partner is super important,

01:02:45.600 --> 01:02:48.770
and building in those
rituals of connection, where

01:02:48.770 --> 01:02:52.510
you can really count on talking
to each other is wonderful,

01:02:52.510 --> 01:02:54.530
helps the marriage.

01:02:54.530 --> 01:02:55.774
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:02:55.774 --> 01:02:56.940
LOGAN URY: Well, that's all.

01:02:56.940 --> 01:02:58.880
That's it for time,
but thank you so much,

01:02:58.880 --> 01:03:03.622
this was really a dream
of mine [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:03.622 --> 01:03:05.369
